# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: li-fi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Optical communications, in various forms, have been used for thousands of years.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The ancient Greeks used a coded alphabetic system of signalling with torches developed by Cleoxenus, Democleitus and Polybius.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In the modern era, semaphores and wireless solar telegraphs called heliographs were developed, using coded signals to communicate with their recipients.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In 1880, Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter created the photophone, at Bell's newly established Volta Laboratory in Washington, DC.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Bell considered it his most important invention.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The device allowed for the transmission of sound on a beam of light.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] On June 3, 1880, Bell conducted the world's first wireless telephone transmission between two buildings, some 213 meters (699 feet) apart.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Its first practical use came in military communication systems many decades later, first for optical telegraphy.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] German colonial troops used heliograph telegraphy transmitters during the Herero Wars starting in 1904, in German South-West Africa (today's Namibia) as did British, French, US or Ottoman signals.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Optical telephone communications were tested at the end of the war, but not introduced at troop level.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In addition, special blinkgeräts were used for communication with airplanes, balloons, and tanks, with varying success.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] A major technological step was to replace the Morse code by modulating optical waves in speech transmission.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Carl Zeiss, Jena developed the **Lichtsprechgerät* 80/80* (literal translation: optical speaking device) that the German army used in their World War II anti-aircraft defense units, or in bunkers at the Atlantic Wall.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The invention of lasers in the 1960s revolutionized free-space optics.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Military organizations were particularly interested and boosted their development.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] However, laser-based free-space optics lost market momentum when the installation of optical fiber networks for civilian uses was at its peak.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Many simple and inexpensive consumer remote controls use low-speed communication using infrared (IR) light.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] This is known as consumer IR technologies.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space point-to-point optical links can be implemented using infrared laser light, although low-data-rate communication over short distances is possible using LEDs.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Infrared Data Association (IrDA) technology is a very simple form of free-space optical communications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] On the communications side the FSO technology is considered as a part of the optical wireless communications applications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space optics can be used for communications between spacecraft.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The reliability of FSO units has always been a problem for commercial telecommunications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Consistently, studies find too many dropped packets and signal errors over small ranges (400 to 500 meters (1,300 to 1,600 ft)).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] This is from both independent studies, such as in the Czech Republic, as well as internal studies, such as one conducted by MRV FSO staff.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Military based studies consistently produce longer estimates for reliability, projecting the maximum range for terrestrial links is of the order of 2 to 3 km (1.2 to 1.9 mi).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] All studies agree the stability and quality of the link is highly dependent on atmospheric factors such as rain, fog, dust and heat.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Relays may be employed to extend the range for FSO communications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] TMEX USA ran two eight-mile links between Laredo, Texas and Nuevo Laredo, Mexico from 1998 to 2002.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The links operated at 155 Mbit/s and reliably carried phone calls and internet service.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The main reason terrestrial communications have been limited to non-commercial telecommunications functions is fog.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Fog often prevents FSO laser links over 500 meters (1,600 ft) from achieving a year-round availability sufficient for commercial services.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Several entities are continually attempting to overcome these key disadvantages to FSO communications and field a system with a better quality of service.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] DARPA has sponsored over US$130 million in research toward this effort, with the ORCA and ORCLE programs.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Other non-government groups are fielding tests to evaluate different technologies that some claim have the ability to address key FSO adoption challenges.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] As of October 2014, none have fielded a working system that addresses the most common atmospheric events.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] FSO research from 1998 to 2006 in the private sector totaled $407.1 million, divided primarily among four start-up companies.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] One private company published a paper on November 20, 2014, claiming they had achieved commercial reliability (99.999% availability) in extreme fog.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] There is no indication this product is currently commercially available.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The massive advantages of laser communication in space have multiple space agencies racing to develop a stable space communication platform, with many significant demonstrations and achievements.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The first gigabit laser-based communication was achieved by the European Space Agency and called the European Data Relay System (EDRS) on November 28, 2014.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The system is operational and is being used on a daily basis.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In December 2023, the Australian National University (ANU) demonstrated its Quantum Optical Ground Station at its Mount Stromlo Observatory.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] QOGS uses adaptive optics and lasers as part of a telescope, to create a bi-directional communications system capable of supporting the NASA Artemis program to the Moon.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] A two-way distance record for communication was set by the Mercury laser altimeter instrument aboard the *MESSENGER* spacecraft.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] It was able to communicate across a distance of 24 million km (15 million mi), as the craft neared Earth on a fly-by in May 2005.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The previous record had been set with a one-way detection of laser light from Earth by the Galileo probe, of 6 million km (3.7 million mi) in 1992.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2013, NASA used lasers to beam an image of the Mona Lisa to the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter roughly 390,000 km (240,000 mi) away.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] To compensate for atmospheric interference, an error correction code algorithm similar to that used in CDs was implemented.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In the early morning hours of October 18, 2013, NASA's Lunar Laser Communication Demonstration (LLCD) transmitted data from lunar orbit to Earth at a rate of 622 megabits per second (Mbit/s).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] LLCD was flown aboard the Lunar Atmosphere and Dust Environment Explorer (LADEE) spacecraft, whose primary science mission was to investigate the tenuous and exotic atmosphere that exists around the Moon.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Between April and July 2014 NASA's OPALS instrument successfully uploaded 175 megabytes in 3.5 seconds and downloaded 200–300 MB in 20 s.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Their system was also able to re-acquire tracking after the signal was lost due to cloud cover.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] On December 7, 2021 NASA launched the Laser Communications Relay Demonstration (LCRD), which aims to relay data between spacecraft in geosynchronous orbit and ground stations.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD is NASA's first two-way, end-to-end optical relay.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD uses two ground stations, Optical Ground Station (OGS)-1 and -2, at Table Mountain Observatory in California, and Haleakalā, Hawaii.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] One of LCRD's first operational users is the Integrated LCRD Low-Earth Orbit User Modem and Amplifier Terminal (ILLUMA-T), on the International Space Station.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The terminal will receive high-resolution science data from experiments and instruments on board the space station and then transfer this data to LCRD, which will then transmit it to a ground station.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] After the data arrives on Earth, it will be delivered to mission operation centers and mission scientists.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The ILLUMA-T payload was sent to the ISS in late 2023 on SpaceX CRS-29, and achieved first light on December 5, 2023.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] On April 28, 2023, NASA and its partners achieved 200 gigabit per second (Gbit/s) throughput on a space-to-ground optical link between a satellite in orbit and Earth.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] This was achieved by the TeraByte InfraRed Delivery (TBIRD) system, mounted on NASA's Pathfinder Technology Demonstrator 3 (PTD-3) satellite.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Various satellite constellations that are intended to provide global broadband coverage, such as SpaceX Starlink, employ laser communication for inter-satellite links.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] This effectively creates a space-based optical mesh network between the satellites.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In 2001, Twibright Labs released RONJA Metropolis, an open-source DIY 10 Mbit/s full-duplex LED FSO system that can span 1.4 km (0.87 mi).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In 2004, a visible light communication consortium was formed in Japan.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] This was based on work from researchers that used a white LED-based space lighting system for indoor local area network (LAN) communications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] These systems present advantages over traditional UHF RF-based systems from improved isolation between systems, the size and cost of receivers/transmitters, RF licensing laws and by combining space lighting and communication into the same system.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2009, a task force for visible light communication was formed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers working group for wireless personal area network standards known as IEEE 802.15.7.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Amateur radio operators have achieved significantly farther distances using incoherent sources of light from high-intensity LEDs.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] However, physical limitations of the equipment used limited bandwidths to about 4 kHz.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The high sensitivities required of the detector to cover such distances made the internal capacitance of the photodiode used a dominant factor in the high-impedance amplifier which followed it, thus naturally forming a low-pass filter with a cut-off frequency in the 4 kHz range.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Lasers can reach very high data rates which are comparable to fiber communications.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Projected data rates and future data rate claims vary.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] A low-cost white LED (GaN-phosphor) which could be used for space lighting can typically be modulated up to 20 MHz.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Data rates of over 100 Mbit/s can be achieved using efficient modulation schemes and Siemens claimed to have achieved over 500 Mbit/s in 2010.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Research published in 2009, used a similar system for traffic control of automated vehicles with LED traffic lights.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In September 2013, pureLiFi, the Edinburgh start-up working on Li-Fi, also demonstrated high speed point-to-point connectivity using any off-the-shelf LED light bulb.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] In previous work, high bandwidth specialist LEDs have been used to achieve the high data rates.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The new system, the Li-1st, maximizes the available optical bandwidth for any LED device, thereby reducing the cost and improving the performance of deploying indoor FSO systems.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] The light beam can be very narrow, which makes FSO hard to intercept, improving security.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Encryption can secure the data traversing the link.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] FSO provides vastly improved electromagnetic interference (EMI) behavior compared to using microwaves.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] These factors cause an attenuated receiver signal and lead to higher bit error ratio (BER).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] To overcome these issues, vendors found some solutions, like multi-beam or multi-path architectures, which use more than one sender and more than one receiver.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Some state-of-the-art devices also have larger fade margin (extra power, reserved for rain, smog, fog).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] To keep an eye-safe environment, good FSO systems have a limited laser power density and support laser classes 1 or 1M.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Atmospheric and fog attenuation, which are exponential in nature, limit practical range of FSO devices to several kilometers.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] However, free-space optics based on 1550 nm wavelength, have considerably lower optical loss than free-space optics using 830 nm wavelength, in dense fog conditions.
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] FSO using wavelength 1550 nm system are capable of transmitting several times higher power than systems with 850 nm and are safe to the human eye (1M class).
[src:li-fi/free-space-optical-communication] Additionally, some free-space optics, such as EC SYSTEM, ensure higher connection reliability in bad weather conditions by constantly monitoring link quality to regulate laser diode transmission power with built-in automatic gain control.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Unlike Wi-Fi, which uses radio frequency via an electric voltage in an antenna to transmit data, Li-Fi uses the modulation of light intensity.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Li-Fi is able to function in areas otherwise susceptible to electromagnetic interference (e.g. aircraft cabins, hospitals, or military applications).
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Li-Fi is a derivative of optical wireless communications (OWC) technology, which uses light from light-emitting diodes (LEDs) as a medium to deliver mobile, high-speed network communication in a manner similar to that of Wi-Fi.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Visible light communications (VLC) works by switching the current to the LEDs off and on at a very high speed, beyond the human eye's ability to notice.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The light waves cannot penetrate walls which translates to a shorter range and a lower potential of interception relative to Wi-Fi.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Direct line of sight is not always necessary for Li-Fi to transmit a signal as light may reflect off walls, mirrors or other reflective objects.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Li-Fi can potentially be useful in electromagnetic sensitive areas without causing electromagnetic interference.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Both Wi-Fi and Li-Fi transmit data over the electromagnetic spectrum, but whereas Wi-Fi utilizes radio waves, Li-Fi uses visible, ultraviolet, and infrared light.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Researchers have reached data rates of over 224 Gbit/s.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] While several companies produce Li-Fi products such as PureLiFi, Signify, Oledcomm, Terra Ferma and others; Wi-Fi and cellular remain the predominant communications technology for consumers, business, industrial and military applications.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The first commercially available Li-Fi system was presented at the 2014 Mobile World Congress in Barcelona.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Since Li-Fi's short wavelengths are unable to penetrate walls, transmitters would need to be installed in every room of a building to ensure even Li-Fi distribution.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The high installation costs associated with this requirement to achieve a level of practicality of the technology is one of the potential downsides.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The initial research on Visible Light Communication (VLC) was published by the Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications in September 2009, showcasing data rates of 125 Mbit/s over a 5 m distance using a standard white LED.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In 2010, transmission rates were already increased to 513 Mbit/s using the DMT modulation format.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] During his 2011 TED Global Talk, Professor Harald Haas, a Mobile Communications expert at the University of Edinburgh, introduced the term *Li-Fi* while discussing the concept of "wireless data from every light".
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The general term *visible light communication* (VLC), whose history dates back to the 1880s, includes any use of the visible light portion of the electromagnetic spectrum to transmit information.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The D-Light project, funded from January 2010 to January 2012 at Edinburgh's Institute for Digital Communications, was instrumental in advancing this technology, with Haas also contributing to the establishment of a company for its commercialization.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The practical demonstration of VLC technology using Li-Fi took place in 2012, with transmission rates exceeding 1 Gbit/s achieved under laboratory conditions.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In 2013, laboratory tests achieved speed of up to 10 Gbit/s.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] By August 2013, data rates of approximately 1.6 Gbit/s were demonstrated over a single color LED.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] A significant milestone was reached in September 2013 when it was stated that Li-Fi, or VLC systems in general, did not absolutely require line-of-sight conditions.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In October 2013, it was reported Chinese manufacturers were working on Li-Fi development kits.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In April 2014, the Russian company Stins Coman announced the BeamCaster Li-Fi wireless local network, capable of data transfer speeds up to 10 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:li-fi/li-fi] They foresee boosting speeds up to 40 Gbit/s in the near future.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In the same year, Sisoft, a Mexican company, set a new record by transferring data at speeds of up to 80 Gbit/s across a light spectrum emitted by LED lamps.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Current offerings by purelifi, Signify, oledcomm and Terra Ferma suggest Li-Fi full-duplex communications links can achieve over 1.0 Gbit/s.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] A study published by IEEE in 2021 suggests speeds of 224 Gbit/s are achievable.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In June 2018, Li-Fi successfully underwent testing at a BMW plant in Munich for industrial applications under the auspices of the Fraunhofer Heinrich-Hertz-Institute.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In August 2018, Kyle Academy in Scotland, piloted the usage within its premises, enabling students to receive data through rapid on–off transitions of room lighting.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In June 2019, Oledcomm, a French company, showcased its Li-Fi technology at the 2019 Paris Air Show.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In January 2025, Terra Ferma, a USA company announced the launch of their Helios and Fortis Li-Fi product lines for US and NATO Government and Military applications.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Like Wi-Fi, Li-Fi is wireless and uses similar 802.11 protocols, but it also uses ultraviolet, infrared, and visible light communication (VLC).
[src:li-fi/li-fi] One part of VLC is modeled after communication protocols established by the IEEE 802 workgroup.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The introduction of O-OFDM means that a new drive for standardization of optical wireless communications is required.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Nonetheless, the IEEE 802.15.7 standard defines the physical layer (PHY) and media access control (MAC) layer.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The standard is able to deliver enough data rates to transmit audio, video, and multimedia services.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] It takes into account optical transmission mobility, its compatibility with artificial lighting present in infrastructures, and the interference which may be generated by ambient lighting.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The MAC layer permits using the link with the other layers as with the TCP/IP protocol.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The modulation formats recognized for PHY I and PHY II are on–off keying (OOK) and variable pulse-position modulation (VPPM).
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The Manchester coding used for the PHY I and PHY II layers includes the clock inside the transmitted data by representing a logic 0 with an OOK symbol "01" and a logic 1 with an OOK symbol "10", all with a DC component.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The DC component avoids light extinction in case of an extended run of logic 0's.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In July 2023, the IEEE published the 802.11bb standard for light-based networking, intended to provide a vendor-neutral standard for the Li-Fi market.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Most remotely operated underwater vehicles (ROVs) are controlled by wired connections.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] The length of their cabling places a hard limit on their operational range, and other potential factors such as the cable's weight and fragility may be restrictive.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Since light can travel through water, Li-Fi–based communications could offer much greater mobility.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Li-Fi's utility is limited by the distance light can penetrate water.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Significant amounts of light do not penetrate further than 200 meters (660 ft).
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Past 1,000 meters (3,300 ft), no light penetrates.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Efficient communication of data is possible in airborne environments such as a commercial passenger aircraft utilizing Li-Fi.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Using this light-based data transmission will not interfere with equipment on the aircraft that relies on radio waves, such as its radar.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Increasingly, medical facilities are using remote examinations and even procedures.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Li-Fi systems could offer a better system to transmit low-latency, high-volume data.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Besides providing a higher speed, light waves also have reduced effects on medical instruments.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] An example of this would be the possibility of wireless devices being used in MRIs similar radio sensitive procedures.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Another application of Li‑Fi in hospitals is localisation of assets and personnel.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Street lamps can be used to display advertisements for nearby businesses or attractions on cellular devices as an individual passes through.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] A customer walking into a store and passing through the store's front lights can show current sales and promotions on the customer's cellular device.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] In warehousing, indoor positioning and navigation is a crucial element.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] 3D positioning helps robots to get a more detailed and realistic visual experience.
[src:li-fi/li-fi] Visible light from LED bulbs is used to send messages to the robots and other receivers and hence can be used to calculate the positioning of the objects.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The process encodes information in the form of a message signal modulated onto a carrier signal to be transmitted.
[src:li-fi/modulation] For example, the message signal might be an audio signal representing sound from a microphone, a video signal representing moving images from a video camera, or a digital signal representing a sequence of binary digits, a bitstream from a computer.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Carrier waves are necessary when the frequency of the message is too low to practically transmit.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Generally, receiving a radio wave requires a radio antenna with a length that is one-fourth of the wavelength of the transmitted wave.
[src:li-fi/modulation] For low-frequency radio waves, wavelength is on the scale of kilometers and building such a large antenna is not practical.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Another purpose of modulation is to transmit multiple channels of information through a single communication medium, using frequency-division multiplexing (FDM).
[src:li-fi/modulation] For example, in cable television (which uses FDM), many carrier signals, each modulated with a different television channel, are transported through a single cable to customers.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Since each carrier occupies a different frequency, the channels do not interfere with each other.
[src:li-fi/modulation] At the destination end, the carrier signal is demodulated to extract the information-bearing modulation signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] A **modulator** is a device or circuit that performs modulation.
[src:li-fi/modulation] A **demodulator** (sometimes *detector*) is a circuit that performs demodulation, the inverse of modulation.
[src:li-fi/modulation] A modem (from **mod**ulator–**dem**odulator), used in bidirectional communication, can perform both operations.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The lower frequency band occupied by the modulation signal is called the *baseband*, while the higher frequency band occupied by the modulated carrier is called the *passband*.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Signal modulation techniques are fundamental methods used in wireless communication to encode information onto a carrier wave by varying its amplitude, frequency, or phase.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In **analog modulation**, an analog modulation signal is "impressed" on the carrier.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Examples are amplitude modulation (AM) in which the amplitude (strength) of the carrier wave is varied by the modulation signal, and frequency modulation (FM) in which the frequency of the carrier wave is varied by the modulation signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] These were the earliest types of modulation, and are used to transmit an audio signal representing sound in AM and FM radio broadcasting.
[src:li-fi/modulation] More recent systems use **digital modulation**, which impresses a digital signal consisting of a sequence of binary digits (bits), a bitstream, on the carrier, by means of mapping bits to elements from a discrete alphabet to be transmitted.
[src:li-fi/modulation] This alphabet can consist of a set of real or complex numbers, or sequences, like oscillations of different frequencies, so-called frequency-shift keying (FSK) modulation.
[src:li-fi/modulation] A more complicated digital modulation method that employs multiple carriers, orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM), is used in WiFi networks, digital radio stations and digital cable television transmission.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In analog modulation, the modulation is applied continuously in response to the analog information signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In digital modulation, an analog carrier signal is modulated by a discrete signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Digital modulation methods can be considered as digital-to-analog conversion and the corresponding demodulation or detection as analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The changes in the carrier signal are chosen from a finite number of M alternative symbols (the *modulation alphabet*).
[src:li-fi/modulation] According to one definition of digital signal, the modulated signal is a digital signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] According to another definition, the modulation is a form of digital-to-analog conversion.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Most textbooks would consider digital modulation schemes as a form of digital transmission, synonymous to data transmission; very few would consider it as analog transmission.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In Quadrature amplitude modulation (QAM), an in-phase signal (or I, with one example being a cosine waveform) and a quadrature phase signal (or Q, with an example being a sine wave) are amplitude modulated with a finite number of amplitudes and then summed.
[src:li-fi/modulation] It can be seen as a two-channel system, each channel using ASK.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The resulting signal is equivalent to a combination of PSK and ASK.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In all of the above methods, each of these phases, frequencies or amplitudes are assigned a unique pattern of binary bits.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Usually, each phase, frequency or amplitude encodes an equal number of bits.
[src:li-fi/modulation] This number of bits comprises the *symbol* that is represented by the particular phase, frequency or amplitude.
[src:li-fi/modulation] If the alphabet consists of $M=2^{N}$ alternative symbols, each symbol represents a message consisting of *N* bits.
[src:li-fi/modulation] If the symbol rate (also known as the baud rate) is $f_{S}$ symbols/second (or baud), the data rate is $Nf_{S}$ bit/second.
[src:li-fi/modulation] For example, with an alphabet consisting of 16 alternative symbols, each symbol represents 4 bits.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Thus, the data rate is four times the baud rate.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In the case of PSK, or ASK, where the carrier frequency of the modulated signal is constant, the modulation alphabet is often conveniently represented on a constellation diagram, showing the amplitude of the I signal at the x-axis, and the amplitude of the Q signal at the y-axis for each symbol.
[src:li-fi/modulation] PSK and ASK, and sometimes also FSK, are often generated and detected using the principle of QAM.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The I and Q signals can be combined into a complex-valued signal *I*+*jQ* (where *j* is the imaginary unit).
[src:li-fi/modulation] The resulting so-called equivalent lowpass signal or equivalent baseband signal is a complex-valued representation of the real-valued modulated physical signal (the so-called passband signal or RF signal).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Map the codewords to attributes, for example, amplitudes of the I and Q signals (the equivalent low-pass signal), or frequency or phase values.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Adapt pulse shaping or some other filtering to limit the bandwidth and form the spectrum of the equivalent low-pass signal, typically using digital signal processing.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Perform digital to analog conversion (DAC) of the I and Q signals (since today all of the above is normally achieved using digital signal processing, DSP).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Generate a high-frequency sine carrier waveform, and perhaps also a cosine quadrature component.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Carry out the modulation, for example, by multiplying the sine and cosine waveforms with the I and Q signals, resulting in the equivalent low-pass signal being frequency shifted to the modulated passband signal or RF signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Sometimes this is achieved using DSP technology, for example, direct digital synthesis using a waveform table, instead of analog signal processing.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In that case, the above DAC step should be done after this step.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Amplification and analog bandpass filtering to avoid harmonic distortion and periodic spectrum.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Automatic gain control, AGC (to compensate for attenuation, for example fading).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Frequency shifting of the RF signal to the equivalent baseband I and Q signals, or to an intermediate frequency (IF) signal, by multiplying the RF signal with a local oscillator sine wave and cosine wave frequency (see the superheterodyne receiver principle).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Sampling and analog-to-digital conversion (ADC) (sometimes before or instead of the above point, for example by means of undersampling).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Equalization filtering, for example, a matched filter, compensation for multipath propagation, time spreading, phase distortion and frequency selective fading, to avoid intersymbol interference and symbol distortion.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Detection of the amplitudes of the I and Q signals, or the frequency or phase of the IF signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Quantization of the amplitudes, frequencies or phases to the nearest allowed symbol values.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Mapping of the quantized amplitudes, frequencies or phases to codewords (bit groups).
[src:li-fi/modulation] Parallel-to-serial conversion of the codewords into a bit stream.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Pass the resultant bit stream on for further processing, such as removal of any error-correcting codes.
[src:li-fi/modulation] As is common to all digital communication systems, the design of both the modulator and demodulator must be done simultaneously.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Digital modulation schemes are possible because the transmitter-receiver pair has prior knowledge of how data is encoded and represented in the communications system.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In all digital communication systems, both the modulator at the transmitter and the demodulator at the receiver are structured so that they perform inverse operations.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Asynchronous methods do not require a receiver reference clock signal that is phase synchronized with the sender carrier signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] In this case, modulation symbols (rather than bits, characters, or data packets) are asynchronously transferred.
[src:li-fi/modulation] MSK and GMSK are particular cases of continuous phase modulation.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Indeed, MSK is a particular case of the sub-family of CPM known as continuous-phase frequency-shift keying (CPFSK) which is defined by a rectangular frequency pulse (i.e. a linearly increasing phase pulse) of one-symbol-time duration (total response signaling).
[src:li-fi/modulation] OFDM is based on the idea of frequency-division multiplexing (FDM), but the multiplexed streams are all parts of a single original stream.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The bit stream is split into several parallel data streams, each transferred over its own sub-carrier using some conventional digital modulation scheme.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The modulated subcarriers are summed to form an OFDM signal.
[src:li-fi/modulation] This dividing and recombining help with handling channel impairments.
[src:li-fi/modulation] OFDM is considered as a modulation technique rather than a multiplex technique since it transfers one bit stream over one communication channel using one sequence of so-called OFDM symbols.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Of the two kinds of RF power amplifier, switching amplifiers (Class D amplifiers) cost less and use less battery power than linear amplifiers of the same output power.
[src:li-fi/modulation] However, they only work with relatively constant-amplitude-modulation signals such as angle modulation (FSK or PSK) and CDMA, but not with QAM and OFDM.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Automatic digital modulation recognition in intelligent communication systems is one of the most important issues in software-defined radio and cognitive radio.
[src:li-fi/modulation] According to incremental expanse of intelligent receivers, automatic modulation recognition becomes a challenging topic in telecommunication systems and computer engineering.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Such systems have many civil and military applications.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Moreover, blind recognition of modulation type is an important problem in commercial systems, especially in software-defined radio.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Usually, in such systems, there are some extra information for system configuration, but considering blind approaches in intelligent receivers, we can reduce information overload and increase transmission performance.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Obviously, with no knowledge of the transmitted data and many unknown parameters at the receiver, such as the signal power, carrier frequency and phase offsets, timing information, etc., blind identification of the modulation is made fairly difficult.
[src:li-fi/modulation] This becomes even more challenging in real-world scenarios with multipath fading, frequency-selective and time-varying channels.
[src:li-fi/modulation] There are two main approaches to automatic modulation recognition.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The first approach uses likelihood-based methods to assign an input signal to a proper class.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Another recent approach is based on feature extraction.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Digital baseband modulation changes the characteristics of a baseband signal, i.e., one without a carrier at a higher frequency.
[src:li-fi/modulation] This can be used as an equivalent signal to be later frequency-converted to a carrier frequency, or for direct communication in baseband.
[src:li-fi/modulation] The latter methods both involve relatively simple line codes, as often used in local buses, and complicated baseband signalling schemes such as used in DSL.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Pulse modulation schemes aim at transferring a narrowband analog signal over an analog baseband channel as a two-level signal by modulating a pulse wave.
[src:li-fi/modulation] Some pulse modulation schemes also allow the narrowband analog signal to be transferred as a digital signal (i.e., as a quantized discrete-time signal) with a fixed bit rate, which can be transferred over an underlying digital transmission system, for example, some line code.
[src:li-fi/modulation] These are not modulation schemes in the conventional sense since they are not channel coding schemes, but should be considered as source coding schemes, and in some cases, analog-to-digital conversion techniques.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] An optical communication system uses a transmitter, which encodes a message into an optical signal, a channel, which carries the signal to its destination, and a receiver, which reproduces the message from the received optical signal.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] When electronic equipment is not employed the 'receiver' is a person visually observing and interpreting a signal, which may be either simple (such as the presence of a beacon fire) or complex (such as lights using color codes or flashed in a Morse code sequence).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Modern communication relies on optical networking systems using optical fiber, optical amplifiers, lasers, switches, routers, and other related technologies.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Free-space optical communication use lasers to transmit signals in space, while terrestrial forms are naturally limited by geography and weather.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] This article provides a basic introduction to different forms of optical communication.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Visual techniques such as smoke signals, beacon fires, hydraulic telegraphs, ship flags and semaphore lines were the earliest forms of optical communication.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Hydraulic telegraph semaphores date back to the 4th century BCE Greece.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Distress flares are still used by mariners in emergencies, while lighthouses and navigation lights are used to communicate navigation hazards.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The heliograph uses a mirror to reflect sunlight to a distant observer.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] When a signaler tilts the mirror to reflect sunlight, the distant observer sees flashes of light that can be used to transmit a prearranged signaling code.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Naval ships often use signal lamps and Morse code in a similar way.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Aircraft pilots often use visual approach slope indicator (VASI) projected light systems to land safely, especially at night.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Military aircraft landing on an aircraft carrier use a similar system to land correctly on a carrier deck.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The coloured light system communicates the aircraft's height relative to a standard landing glideslope.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] As well, airport control towers still use Aldis lamps to transmit instructions to aircraft whose radios have failed.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] A 'semaphore telegraph', also called a 'semaphore line', 'optical telegraph', 'shutter telegraph chain', 'Chappe telegraph', or 'Napoleonic semaphore', is a system used for conveying information by means of visual signals, using towers with pivoting arms or shutters, also known as blades or paddles.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the mechanical elements; it is read when the shutter is in a fixed position.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Semaphore lines were a precursor of the electrical telegraph.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] They were far faster than post riders for conveying a message over long distances, but far more expensive and less private than the electrical telegraph lines which would later replace them.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The maximum distance that a pair of semaphore telegraph stations can bridge is limited by geography, weather and the availability of light; thus, in practical use, most optical telegraphs used lines of relay stations to bridge longer distances.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Each relay station would also require its complement of skilled operator-observers to convey messages back and forth across the line.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The modern design of semaphores was first foreseen by the British polymath Robert Hooke, who first gave a vivid and comprehensive outline of visual telegraphy in a 1684 submission to the Royal Society.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] His proposal (which was motivated by military concerns following the Battle of Vienna the preceding year) was not put into practice during his lifetime.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The first operational optical semaphore line arrived in 1792, created by the French engineer Claude Chappe and his brothers, who succeeded in covering France with a network of 556 stations stretching a total distance of 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] It was used for military and national communications until the 1850s.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Many national services adopted signaling systems different from the Chappe system.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] For example, Britain and Sweden adopted systems of shuttered panels (in contradiction to the Chappe brothers' contention that angled rods are more visible).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] In Spain, the engineer Agustín de Betancourt developed his own system which was adopted by that state.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] This system was considered by many experts in Europe better than Chappe's, even in France.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] These systems were popular in the late 18th to early 19th century but could not compete with the electrical telegraph, and went completely out of service by 1880.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Semaphore flags are the system for conveying information at a distance by means of visual signals with hand-held flags, rods, disks, paddles, or occasionally bare or gloved hands.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the flags, objects or arms; it is read when they are in a fixed position.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Semaphores were adopted and widely used (with hand-held flags replacing the mechanical arms of shutter semaphores) in the maritime world in the 19th century.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] They are still used during underway replenishment at sea and are acceptable for emergency communication in daylight or, using lighted wands instead of flags, at night.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The newer flag semaphore system uses two short poles with square flags, which a signaler holds in different positions to convey letters of the alphabet and numbers.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The transmitter holds one pole in each hand, and extends each arm in one of eight possible directions.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Except for in the rest position, the flags cannot overlap.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The flags are colored differently based on whether the signals are sent by sea or by land.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] At sea, the flags are colored red and yellow (the Oscar flags), while on land, they are white and blue (the Papa flags).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Flags are not required, they just make the characters more obvious.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Signal lamps (such as Aldis lamps), are visual signaling devices for optical communication (typically using Morse code).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Modern signal lamps are a focused lamp which can produce a pulse of light.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] In large versions this pulse is achieved by opening and closing shutters mounted in front of the lamp, either via a manually operated pressure switch or, in later versions, automatically.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] With hand held lamps, a concave mirror is tilted by a trigger to focus the light into pulses.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The lamps are usually equipped with some form of optical sight, and are most commonly deployed on naval vessels and also used in airport control towers with coded aviation light signals.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Aviation light signals are used in the case of a radio failure, an aircraft not equipped with a radio, or in the case of a hearing-impaired pilot.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Air traffic controllers have long used signal light guns to direct such aircraft.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The light gun's lamp has a focused bright beam capable of emitting three different colors: red, white and green.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] These colors may be flashing or steady, and provide different instructions to aircraft in flight or on the ground (for example, "cleared to land" or "cleared for takeoff").
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Pilots can acknowledge the instructions by wiggling their plane's wings, moving their ailerons if they are on the ground, or by flashing their landing or navigation lights during night time.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Only 12 simple standardized instructions are directed at aircraft using signal light guns as the system is not utilized with Morse code.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] A heliograph (Greek: Ἥλιος *helios*, meaning "sun", and γραφειν *graphein*, meaning "write") is a wireless solar telegraph that signals by flashes of sunlight (generally using Morse code) reflected by a mirror.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The flashes are produced by momentarily pivoting the mirror, or by interrupting the beam with a shutter.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The heliograph was a simple but effective instrument for instantaneous optical communication over long distances during the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Its main uses were in military, surveys and forest protection work.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] They were standard issue in the British and Australian armies until the 1960s, and were used by the Pakistani army as late as 1975.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] In the present day a variety of electronic systems optically transmit and receive information carried by pulses of light.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Fiber-optic communication cables are employed to carry electronic data and telephone traffic.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Free-space optical communications are also used every day in various applications.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Optical fiber is the most common type of channel for optical communications.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The transmitters in optical fiber links are generally light-emitting diodes (LEDs) or laser diodes.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Infrared light is used more commonly than visible light, because optical fibers transmit infrared wavelengths with less attenuation and dispersion.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The signal encoding is typically simple intensity modulation, although historically optical phase and frequency modulation have been demonstrated in the lab.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The need for periodic signal regeneration was largely superseded by the introduction of the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which extended link distances at significantly lower cost.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The commercial introduction of dense wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) in 1996 by Ciena Corp was the real start of optical networking.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] WDM is now the common basis of nearly every high-capacity optical system in the world.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The first optical communication systems were designed and delivered to the U.S.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Army and Chevron by Optelecom, Inc., the venture co-founded by Gordon Gould, the inventor of the optical amplifier and the laser.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The photophone (originally given an alternate name, radiophone) is a communication device which allowed for the transmission of speech on a beam of light.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] It was invented jointly by Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter on February 19, 1880, at Bell's 1325 'L' Street laboratory in Washington, D.C.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Both were later to become full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association, created and financed by Bell.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message of considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School to the window of Bell's laboratory, some 213 meters (about 700 ft) away.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Bell believed the photophone was his most important invention.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage starting in the 1980s.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] The master patent for the photophone (U.S. patent 235,199 *Apparatus for Signalling and Communicating, called Photophone*), was issued in December 1880, many decades before its principles came to have practical applications.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Free-space optics (FSO) systems are employed for 'last mile' telecommunications and can function over distances of several kilometers as long as there is a clear line of sight between the source and the destination, and the optical receiver can reliably decode the transmitted information.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Other free-space systems can provide high-data-rate, long-range links using small, low-mass, low-power-consumption subsystems which make them suitable for communications in space.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Various planned satellite constellations intended to provide global broadband coverage take advantage of these benefits and employ laser communication for inter-satellite links between the several hundred to thousand satellites effectively creating a space-based optical mesh network.
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] More generally, transmission of unguided optical signals is known as optical wireless communications (OWC).
[src:li-fi/optical-communication] Examples include medium-range visible light communication and short-distance IrDA, using infrared LEDs.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In telecommunications, **visible light communication** (**VLC**) is the use of visible light (light with a frequency of 400–800 THz, wavelength of 780–375 nm) as a transmission medium.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] VLC is a subset of optical wireless communications technologies.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The technology uses fluorescent lamps (ordinary lamps, not special communications devices) to transmit signals at 10 kbit/s, or LEDs for up to 500 Mbit/s over short distances.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Systems such as RONJA can transmit at full Ethernet speed (10 Mbit/s) over distances of 1–2 kilometres (0.6–1.2 mi).
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Specially designed electronic devices generally containing a photodiode receive signals from light sources, although in some cases a cell phone camera or a digital camera will be sufficient.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The image sensor used in these devices is in fact an array of photodiodes (pixels), and in some applications its use may be preferred over a single photodiode.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Such a sensor may provide either multi-channel (down to 1 pixel = 1 channel) or a spatial awareness of multiple light sources.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] VLC can be used as a communications medium for ubiquitous computing, because light-producing devices (such as indoor/outdoor lamps, TVs, traffic signs, commercial displays and car headlights/taillights) are used everywhere.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] One of the main characteristics of VLC is the incapacity of light to surpass physical opaque barriers.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] A promising application of VLC is the Indoor Positioning System (IPS), an analogue to GPS which is built to operate in enclosed spaces where GPS satellite transmissions cannot reach.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] For instance, commercial buildings, shopping malls, parking garages, as well as subways and tunnel systems are all possible applications for VLC-based indoor positioning systems.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Additionally, once the VLC lamps are able to perform lighting at the same time as data transmission, it can simply occupy the installation of traditional single-function lamps.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Other applications for VLC involve communication between appliances of a smart home or office.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] With increasing IoT-capable devices, connectivity through traditional radio waves might be subjected to interference.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Light bulbs with VLC capabilities can transmit data and commands for such devices.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The history of visible light communications dates back to the 1880s in Washington, D.C., when the Scottish-born scientist Alexander Graham Bell invented the photophone, which transmitted speech on modulated sunlight over several hundred meters.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] This pre-dates the transmission of speech by radio.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] More recent work began in 2003 at Nakagawa Laboratory, in Keio University, Japan, using LEDs to transmit data by visible light.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Since then there have been numerous research activities focussed on VLC.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In 2006, researchers from CICTR at Penn State proposed a combination of power line communication (PLC) and white light LED to provide broadband access for indoor applications.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] This research suggested that VLC could be deployed as a perfect last-mile solution in the future.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In January 2010 a team of researchers from Siemens and Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications, Heinrich Hertz Institute, in Berlin, demonstrated transmission at 500 Mbit/s with a white LED over a distance of 5 metres (16 ft), and 100 Mbit/s over longer distance using five LEDs.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The VLC standardization process is conducted within the IEEE 802.15.7 working group.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Cloud, Minnesota, signed a contract with LVX [1] Minnesota and became the first to commercially deploy this technology.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In July 2011 a presentation at TED Global gave a live demonstration of high-definition video being transmitted from a standard LED lamp, and proposed the term Li-Fi to refer to a subset of VLC technology.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Recently, VLC-based indoor positioning systems have become an attractive topic.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] ABI research forecasts that it could be a key solution to unlocking the $5 billion "indoor location market".
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Publications have been coming from Nakagawa Laboratory, ByteLight filed a patent on a light positioning system using LED digital pulse recognition in March 2012.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] COWA at Penn State and other researchers around the world.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Another recent application is in the world of toys, thanks to cost-efficient and low-complexity implementation, which only requires one microcontroller and one LED as optical front-end.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] VLCs can be used for providing security.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] They are especially useful in body sensor networks and personal area networks.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Recently Organic LEDs (OLED) have been used as optical transceivers to build up VLC communication links up to 10 Mbit/s.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In October 2014, Axrtek launched a commercial bidirectional RGB LED VLC system called MOMO that transmits down and up at speeds of 300 Mbit/s and with a range of 25 feet.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In May 2015, Philips collaborated with supermarket company Carrefour to deliver VLC location-based services to shoppers' smartphones in a hypermarket in Lille, France.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In June 2015, two Chinese companies, Kuang-Chi and Ping An Bank, partnered to introduce a payment card that communicates information through a unique visible light.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In March 2017, Philips set up the first VLC location-based services to shoppers' smartphones in Germany.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The installation was presented at EuroShop in Düsseldorf (5–9 March).
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] As first supermarket in Germany an Edeka supermarket in Düsseldorf-Bilk is using the system, which offers a 30 centimeter positioning accuracy can be achieved, which meets the special demands in food retail.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Indoor positioning systems based on VLC can be used in places such as hospitals, eldercare homes, warehouses, and large, open offices to locate people and control indoor robotic vehicles.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] There is wireless network that for data transmission uses visible light, and does not use intensity modulation of optical sources.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The idea is to use vibration generator instead of optical sources for data transmission.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In order to send data, a modulation of light is required.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] A modulation is the form in which the light signal varies in order to represent different symbols.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Unlike radio transmission, a VLC modulation requires the light signal to be modulated around a positive dc value, responsible for the lighting aspect of the lamp.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The modulation will thus be an alternating signal around the positive dc level, with a high-enough frequency to be imperceptible to the human eye.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] There are several modulation techniques available, forming three main groups: single-carrier modulated transmission (SCMT), multi-carrier modulated transmission (MCMT) and pulse-based transmission (PBT).
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The single-carrier modulated transmission comprises modulation techniques established for traditional forms of transmission, such as radio.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] A sinusoidal wave is added to the lighting DC level, allowing digital information to be coded in the characteristics of the wave.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] By keying between two or several different values of a given characteristic, symbols attributed to each value are transmitted on the light link.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Possible techniques are amplitude-shift keying (ASK), phase-shift keying (PSK) and frequency-shift keying (FSK).
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Out of these three, FSK is capable of larger bitrate transmission once it allows more symbols to be easily differentiated on frequency switching.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] An additional technique called quadrature amplitude modulation (QAM) has also been proposed, where both amplitude and phase of the sinusoidal voltage are keyed simultaneously in order to increase the possible number of symbols.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Multi-carrier modulated transmission works on the same way of single-carrier modulated transmission methods, but embed two or more sinusoidal waves modulated for data transmission.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] This type of modulation is among the hardest and more complex to synthesize and decode.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] However, it presents the advantage of excelling in multipath transmission, where the receptor is not in direct view of the transmitter and therefore makes the transmission depend on reflection of the light in other barriers.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Pulse-based transmission encompasses modulation techniques in which the data is encoded not on a sinusoidal wave, but on a pulsed wave.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Unlike sinusoidal alternating signals, in which the periodic average will always be null, pulsed waves based on high–low states will present inherit average values.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Due to these important implementation advantages, these dimming-capable modulations have been standardized in IEEE 802.15.7, in which are described three modulation techniques: on–off keying (OOK), variable pulse position modulation (VPPM) and color-shift keying (CSK).
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] On the on–off keying technique, the LED is switched on and off repeatedly, and the symbols are differentiated by the pulse width, with a wider pulse representing the logical high "1", while narrower pulses representing logical low "0".
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Because the data is encoded on the pulse width, the information sent will affect the dimming level if not corrected: for instance, a bitstream with several high values "1" will appear brighter than a bitstream with several low values "0".
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In order to avoid this problem, the modulation requires a compensation pulse that will be inserted on the data period whenever necessary to equalize the brightness overall.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The lack of this compensation symbol could introduce perceived flickering, which is undesirable.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Because of the additional compensation pulse, modulating this wave is slightly more complex than modulating the VPPM.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] However, the information encoded on the pulse width is easy to differentiate and decode, so the complexity of the transmitter is balanced by the simplicity of the receiver.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Variable pulse position also switches the LED on and off repeatedly, but encode the symbols on the pulse position inside the data period.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Whenever the pulse is located at the immediate beginning of the data period, the transmitted symbol is standardized as logical low "0", with logical high "1" being composed of pulses that end with the data period.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Because the information is encoded at the location of the pulse inside the data period, both pulses can and will have the same width, and thus, no compensation symbol is required.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Dimming is performed by the transmitting algorithm, that will select the width of the data pulses accordingly.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The lack of a compensation pulse makes VPPM marginally simpler to encode when compared to OOK.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] However, a slightly more complex demodulation compensates for that simplicity on the VPPM technique.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] This decoding complexity mostly comes from the information being encoded at different rising edges for each symbol, which makes the sampling harder in a microcontroller.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Additionally, in order to decode the location of a pulse within the data period, the receptor must be somehow synchronized with the transmitter, knowing exactly when a data period starts and how long it lasts.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] These characteristics makes the demodulation of a VPPM signal slightly more difficult to implement.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Color-shift keying (CSK), outlined in IEEE 802.15.7, is an intensity modulation based modulation scheme for VLC.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] CSK is intensity-based, as the modulated signal takes on an instantaneous color equal to the physical sum of three (red/green/blue) LED instantaneous intensities.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] This modulated signal jumps instantaneously, from symbol to symbol, across different visible colors; hence, CSK can be construed as a form of frequency shifting.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] The LEDs’ transmissions are, therefore, preset to time-average (over the CFF and the CCF) to a specific time-constant color.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] Humans can thus perceive only this preset color that seems constant over time, but cannot perceive the instantaneous color that varies rapidly in time.
[src:li-fi/visible-light-communication] In other words, CSK transmission maintains a constant time-averaged luminous flux, even as its symbol sequence varies rapidly in chromaticity.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The term *wireless* has been used twice in communications history, with slightly different meanings.
[src:li-fi/wireless] It was initially used from about 1890 for the first radio transmitting and receiving technology, as in *wireless telegraphy*, until the new word *radio* replaced it around 1920.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Radio sets in the UK and the English-speaking world that were not portable continued to be referred to as *wireless sets* into the 1960s.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The term *wireless* was revived in the 1980s and 1990s mainly to distinguish digital devices that communicate without wires, such as the examples listed in the previous paragraph, from those that require wires or cables.
[src:li-fi/wireless] This became its primary usage in the 2000s, due to the advent of technologies such as mobile broadband, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wireless operations permit services, such as mobile and interplanetary communications, that are impossible or impractical to implement with the use of wires.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The term is commonly used in the telecommunications industry to refer to telecommunications systems (e.g. radio transmitters and receivers, remote controls, etc.) that use some form of energy (e.g. radio waves and acoustic energy) to transfer information without the use of wires.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Information is transferred in this manner over both short and long distances .
[src:li-fi/wireless] The first wireless telephone conversation occurred in 1880 when Alexander Graham Bell and Charles Sumner Tainter invented the photophone, a telephone that sent audio over a beam of light.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The photophone required sunlight to operate, and a clear line of sight between the transmitter and receiver, which greatly decreased the viability of the photophone in any practical use.
[src:li-fi/wireless] It would be several decades before the photophone's principles found their first practical applications in military communications and later in fiber-optic communications.
[src:li-fi/wireless] A number of wireless electrical signaling schemes including sending electric currents through water and the ground using electrostatic and electromagnetic induction were investigated for telegraphy in the late 19th century before practical radio systems became available.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The Edison system was used by stranded trains during the Great Blizzard of 1888 and earth conductive systems found limited use between trenches during World War I but these systems were never successful economically.
[src:li-fi/wireless] In 1894, Guglielmo Marconi began developing a wireless telegraph system using radio waves, which had been known about since proof of their existence in 1888 by Heinrich Hertz, but discounted as a communication format since they seemed, at the time, to be a short-range phenomenon.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Marconi soon developed a system that was transmitting signals way beyond distances anyone could have predicted (due in part to the signals bouncing off the then unknown ionosphere).
[src:li-fi/wireless] Marconi and Karl Ferdinand Braun were awarded the 1909 Nobel Prize for Physics for their contribution to this form of wireless telegraphy.
[src:li-fi/wireless] In 1898, Nikola Tesla demonstrated the first radio-controlled vessel at Madison Square Garden.
[src:li-fi/wireless] It was a 4-foot long “teleautomaton” boat controlled via a wireless box with levers.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The small boat used radio waves to operate its propeller, rudders, and lights.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The audience was reportedly astonished, with some speculating the boat was being controlled by magic, telepathy, or a trained monkey inside.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Tesla attempted to pitch his invention to the United States Navy as a radio-controlled torpedo or weaponized drone.
[src:li-fi/wireless] However, the Navy was seemingly unimpressed by the idea.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Millimetre wave communication was first investigated by Jagadish Chandra Bose during 1894–1896, when he reached an extremely high frequency of up to 60 GHz in his experiments.
[src:li-fi/wireless] He also introduced the use of semiconductor junctions to detect radio waves, when he patented the radio crystal detector in 1901.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Radio and microwave communication carry information by modulating properties of electromagnetic waves transmitted through space.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Specifically, the transmitter generates artificial electromagnetic waves by applying time-varying electric currents to its antenna.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The waves travel away from the antenna until they eventually reach the antenna of a receiver, which induces an electric current in the receiving antenna.
[src:li-fi/wireless] This current can be detected and demodulated to recreate the information sent by the transmitter.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Optical wireless communications (OWC) is a form of optical communication in which unguided light is used "in the air" (or in outer space), without an optical fiber.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Visible, infrared (IR), or ultraviolet (UV) light is used to carry a wireless signal.
[src:li-fi/wireless] It is generally used in short-range communication; extensions exist for long-range and ultra-long range.
[src:li-fi/wireless] OWC systems operating in the visible band (390–750 nm) are commonly referred to as visible light communication (VLC).
[src:li-fi/wireless] VLC systems take advantage of light-emitting diodes (LEDs) which can be pulsed at very high speeds without a noticeable effect on the lighting output and human eye.
[src:li-fi/wireless] VLC can be possibly used in a wide range of applications including wireless local area networks, wireless personal area networks and vehicular networks, among others.
[src:li-fi/wireless] On the other hand, terrestrial point-to-point OWC systems, also known as the free space optical (FSO) systems, operate at the near IR frequencies (750–1600 nm).
[src:li-fi/wireless] These systems typically use laser transmitters and offer a cost-effective protocol-transparent link with high data rates, i.e., 10 Gbit/s per wavelength, and provide a potential solution for the backhaul bottleneck.
[src:li-fi/wireless] There has also been a growing interest in ultraviolet communication (UVC) as a result of recent progress in solid-state optical sources/detectors operating within solar-blind UV spectrum (200–280 nm).
[src:li-fi/wireless] In this so-called deep UV band, solar radiation is negligible at the ground level and this makes possible the design of photon-counting detectors with wide field-of-view receivers that increase the received energy with little additional background noise.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Such designs are particularly useful for outdoor non-line-of-sight configurations to support low-power short-range UVC such as in wireless sensors and ad-hoc networks.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Free-space optical communication (FSO) is an optical communication technology that uses light propagating in free space to transmit wireless data for telecommunications or computer networking.
[src:li-fi/wireless] "Free space" means the light beams travel through the open air or outer space.
[src:li-fi/wireless] This contrasts with other communication technologies that use light beams traveling through transmission lines such as optical fiber or dielectric "light pipes".
[src:li-fi/wireless] The technology is useful where physical connections are impractical due to high costs or other considerations.
[src:li-fi/wireless] For example, free space optical links are used in cities between office buildings that are not wired for networking, where the cost of running cable through the building and under the street would be prohibitive.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Another widely used example is consumer IR devices such as remote controls and IrDA (Infrared Data Association) networking, which is used as an alternative to WiFi networking to allow laptops, PDAs, printers, and digital cameras to exchange data.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Sonic, especially ultrasonic short-range communication involves the transmission and reception of sound.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Electromagnetic induction only allows short-range communication and power transmission.
[src:li-fi/wireless] It has been used in biomedical situations such as pacemakers, as well as for short-range RFID tags.
[src:li-fi/wireless] AM and FM radios and other electronic devices make use of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The frequencies of the radio spectrum that are available for use for communication are treated as a public resource and are regulated by organizations such as the American Federal Communications Commission, Ofcom in the United Kingdom, the international ITU-R or the European ETSI.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Their regulations determine which frequency ranges can be used for what purpose and by whom.
[src:li-fi/wireless] In the absence of such control or alternative arrangements such as a privatized electromagnetic spectrum, chaos might result if, for example, airlines did not have specific frequencies to work under and an amateur radio operator was interfering with a pilot's ability to land an aircraft.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wireless communication spans the spectrum from 9 kHz to 300 GHz.
[src:li-fi/wireless] One of the best-known examples of wireless technology is the mobile phone, also known as a cellular phone, with more than 6.6 billion mobile cellular subscriptions worldwide as of the end of 2010.
[src:li-fi/wireless] These wireless phones use radio waves from signal-transmission towers to enable their users to make phone calls from many locations worldwide.
[src:li-fi/wireless] They can be used within the range of the mobile telephone site used to house the equipment required to transmit and receive the radio signals from these instruments.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wireless data communications allow wireless networking between desktop computers, laptops, tablet computers, cell phones, and other related devices.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wi-Fi has become the de facto standard for access in private homes, within offices, and at public hotspots.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Some businesses charge customers a monthly fee for service, while others have begun offering it free in an effort to increase the sales of their goods.
[src:li-fi/wireless] are responsible for sensing noise, interference, and activity in data collection networks.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Peripheral devices in computing can also be connected wirelessly, as part of a Wi-Fi network or directly via an optical or radio-frequency (RF) peripheral interface.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Originally these units used bulky, highly local transceivers to mediate between a computer and a keyboard and mouse; however, more recent generations have used smaller, higher-performance devices.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Radio-frequency interfaces, such as Bluetooth or Wireless USB, provide greater ranges of efficient use, usually up to 10 feet, but distance, physical obstacles, competing signals, and even human bodies can all degrade the signal quality.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Concerns about the security of wireless keyboards arose at the end of 2007 when it was revealed that Microsoft's implementation of encryption in some of its 27 MHz models were highly insecure.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wireless energy transfer is a process whereby electrical energy is transmitted from a power source to an electrical load that does not have a built-in power source, without the use of interconnecting wires.
[src:li-fi/wireless] There are two different fundamental methods for wireless energy transfer.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Energy can be transferred using either far-field methods that involve beaming power/lasers, radio or microwave transmissions, or near-field using electromagnetic induction.
[src:li-fi/wireless] Wireless energy transfer may be combined with wireless information transmission in what is known as Wireless Powered Communication.
[src:li-fi/wireless] In 2015, researchers at the University of Washington demonstrated far-field energy transfer using Wi-Fi signals to power cameras.
[src:li-fi/wireless] New wireless technologies, such as mobile body area networks (MBAN), have the capability to monitor blood pressure, heart rate, oxygen level, and body temperature.
[src:li-fi/wireless] The MBAN works by sending low-powered wireless signals to receivers that feed into nursing stations or monitoring sites.
[src:li-fi/wireless] This technology helps with the intentional and unintentional risk of infection or disconnection that arise from wired connections.
